{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ed4669f1-e424-4c60-abda-d8846a6fb096","content":"## What Happened\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, **implicit span conversions** (from `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>`) are now considered in more overload resolution contexts. The compiler resolves `array.Contains(num)` to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(this ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)\n```\n\ninstead of the .NET 9 choice:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<int>(this IEnumerable<int>, int)\n```\n\nSince `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be captured in an expression tree. The tree is emitted referencing the span-based method, and the expression interpreter throws at runtime because it cannot invoke a method with a ref-struct parameter.\n\n## Fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the `IEnumerable<T>` overload:\n\n**Option A — cast the array:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nEither avoids the span overload and keeps the expression tree valid.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fd870f70-2d1a-4f91-9869-ad467ca86d1b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when compiled with `preferInterpretation: true`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nThe real culprit is probably the resolution order for `Contains` — in .NET 10, `MemoryExtensions.Contains`