auses problems in expression trees since they can't properly represent that conversion. The solution would be to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the older overload. I'm reconsidering whether this manifests as a compile-time or runtime error. `) T)` instead of the `Enumerable.Contains` method, and since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct that can't be used in expression trees, the runtime interpreter fails when trying to execute the compiled expression tree even though the C# compiler initially allowed it through.\n\nThe fix is to explicitly route to `Enumerable.Contains` either by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or calling `Enumerable.Contains` directly, bypassing the implicit span conversion that causes the problem. I'm recalling that .NET 9 previews actually had reports of this exact issue—`array.Contains()` breaking in expression trees because the span overload was being selected over the LINQ version. The compiler was supposed to avoid considering span conversions in expression tree contexts, but it's possible that .NET 10 or C# 14 changed the overload resolution rules or expanded implicit span conversions in a way that reintroduced the problem. I'll go with explaining this core issue: implicit span conversions combined with expression trees create a conflict when `MemoryExtensions.Contains` gets picked instead of `Enumerable.Contains`.","outputTokens":3670,"requestId":"C438:1ED388:1E9D896:22793CE:6A07CB6B"},"id":"20fbd707-1249-4f59-8273-6fc42db1199a","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:43:07.269Z","parentId":"27999413-4e76-4777-bb88-c7e79701bd66"}
